SIMPLE: flounder
RECORDS: 3

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Flounder
<hw>Floun"der</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[Cf. Sw.
<ets>flundra</ets>; akin to Dan. <ets>flynder</ets>, Icel.
<ets>fly<?/ra</ets>, G. <ets>flunder</ets>, and perh. to E.
<ets>flounder</ets>, v.i.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <fld>(Zool.)</fld> <def>A
flatfish of the family <fam>Pleuronectid⟦ae⟧</fam>, of many
species.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><note>⟦hand⟧ The common English flounder is <spn>Pleuronectes
flesus</spn>. There are several common American species used as food; as
the smooth flounder (<spn>P. glabra</spn>); the rough or winter flounder
(<spn>P. Americanus</spn>); the summer flounder, or plaice
(<spn>Paralichthys dentatus</spn>), Atlantic coast; and the starry
flounder (<spn>Pleuronectes stellatus</spn>).</note>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <fld>(Bootmaking)</fld> <def>A tool used in crimping boot
fronts.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Flounder</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Flounder
<hw>Floun"der</hw>, <pos>v. i.</pos> <vmorph>[<pos>imp. & p. p.</pos>
<conjf>Floundered</conjf> <pr>(?)</pr>; <pos>p. pr. & vb. n.</pos>
<conjf>Floundering</conjf>.]</vmorph> <ety>[Cf. D. <ets>flodderen</ets>
to flap, splash through mire, E. <ets>flounce</ets>, v.i., and
<ets>flounder</ets> the fish.]</ety> <def>To fling the limbs and body,
as in making efforts to move; to struggle, as a horse in the mire, or as
a fish on land; to roll, toss, and tumble; to flounce.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>They have <qex>floundered</qex> on from blunder to blunder.</q>
<rj><qau>Sir W. Hamilton.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Flounder</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 3 ====
HEADWORD: Flounder
<hw>Floun"der</hw>, <pos>n.</pos> <def>The act of floundering.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

